    "result": {"data":{"challengeNode":{"challenge":{"videoId":null,"videoLocaleIds":null,"bilibiliIds":null,"title":"Task 28","description":"<section id=\"description\">\n<p>When a verb follows a preposition, it often takes the <code>-ing</code> form, known as a gerund. Gerunds are verbs acting as nouns. This rule is common in many English expressions. For example:</p>\n<p><code>After eating dinner, we watched a movie.</code> (<code>eating</code> follows the preposition <code>after</code>)</p>\n<p><code>She is interested in learning Spanish.</code> (<code>learning</code> follows the preposition <code>in</code>)</p>\n<p><code>Before going to bed, I like to read.</code> (<code>going</code> follows the preposition <code>before</code>)</p>\n</section>","challengeType":19,"helpCategory":"English","superBlock":"a2-english-for-developers","block":"learn-how-to-discuss-your-morning-or-evening-routine","fields":{"slug":"/learn/a2-english-for-developers/learn-how-to-discuss-your-morning-or-evening-routine/task-28","blockName":"learn-how-to-discuss-your-morning-or-evening-routine","tests":[]},"question":{"text":"<p>What is the verb Sarah uses after the preposition <code>before</code>?</p>","answers":[{"answer":"<p><code>morning</code></p>","feedback":"<p><code>Morning</code> is a noun and doesn't fit after <code>before</code> in the context of an action related to leaving.</p>"},{"answer":"<p><code>leave</code></p>","feedback":"<p><code>Leave</code> is the base form of the verb, but after a preposition, the verb should be in the <code>-ing</code> form.</p>"},{"answer":"<p><code>leaving</code></p>","feedback":null},{"answer":"<p><code>left</code></p>","feedback":"<p><code>Left</code> is the past tense of <code>leave</code> and isn't used after a preposition to describe an ongoing action.</p>"}],"solution":3},"scene":{"setup":{"background":"company2-breakroom.png","characters":[{"character":"Sarah","position":{"x":50,"y":0,"z":1.4},"opacity":0}],"audio":{"filename":"2.2-1.mp3",